A frame is a snapshot of game state with features at some time t.
Let NUM_FRAMES = 4.
I wanna have NUM_FRAMES: t, t+1, t+10, t_resolved,
where t_resolved is the time in the future when all moving ships have resolved (landed).

Let ACTIONS_DIM = 6 (subject to change).
The actions are (25%, 50%, 75%, 100%, 42, target_planet_resolved + 1)
where
    25%, 50%, 75%, 100% are fractions of the planet's ship count currently.
    42 is a constant.
    target_planet_resolved 
        is the number of ships required to take the planet once all moving ships have resolved,
        if the target planet is already in ally control once ships have resolved, this action is invalid.

Actions are invalid if there are insufficient ships at the source planet.
Actions are invalid if the source planet is not under ally control.

An action (i, j, count) is invalid if the trajectory caused from sending `count` ships from i to j, 
is not "clean" - i.e. the ships don't arrive at the destination in the future - this could be
because they intersect with another planet or intersect the sun.
(I don't see any other reason for obstruction.)

The output action space is therefore (44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM).
Create a valid action mask. I think this mask should also be of shape (44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM).

A planet token consists of information about a planet, the specifics we'll work out later.
Pretty much stuff like:
    * is_mine
    * is_enemy
    * is_neutral
    * is_comet
    * is_orbiting
    * production
    * ships
    * dist_to_sun

Each frame consists of 44 planet tokens along with an 
asymmetric distances matrix D of dims (44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM) 
where D[i][j][action_idx] is the number of turns required to send the ships from i to j, 
starting at this frame. Probably we keep this number as a float instead of one hot.

For invalid actions probably just leave this at 0 and let valid action mask handle it.
So this is looking like (NUM_FRAMES, 44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM).

[UPDATE] The turns/distance tensor is now computed for the DECISION frame (t)
ONLY -> shape (44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM), not (NUM_FRAMES, 44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM). The
policy only acts at t, and the aim solve is ~all the cost, so running it for the
t+1/t+10/t_resolved frames wasn't worth ~4x the work. The lookahead frames still
give temporal context via their planet tokens + presence (those stay
(NUM_FRAMES, 44, ...)). angles and mask are likewise frame-t only.

