OPTIMISATION LOG (encode_obs, ~21-planet states, single-thread):
* baseline (turns for all 4 frames):                       ~30 calls/s (33 ms)
* removed hashmap from projection hot loop:                 ~36 calls/s (28 ms)
* broad-phase cull of far stationary planets + FxHashMap:   ~40 calls/s (25 ms)
  (modest: the swept tests were only ~3ms of the loop; profiling showed the cost
   was spread across the 4-frame full action grid, not any single hot spot.)
* turns/angles/mask at frame t only (above):               ~155 calls/s (6.5 ms)  <-- ~4x
* zero-copy numpy returns (below):                          ~165 calls/s (~6 ms), current
* parallelisation: tried, then REVERTED (kept single-threaded by choice; the
  per-source loop is embarrassingly parallel if we ever want cores x later).

OUTPUT FORMAT: tokens/presence/turns/angles/mask come back as 1-D numpy arrays
(numpy takes ownership of the Rust Vec's buffer -> no copy), plus a `*_shape`
tuple. On the Python side: `f["turns"].reshape(f["turns_shape"])` is a zero-copy
view and `torch.from_numpy(...)` shares the same memory (verified). So encode ->
torch tensors is ~5.9 ms with no copies. planet_ids/frame_offsets/frame_planets
stay plain Python (small, metadata/debug only). The wall-clock win over the old
Vec->PyList path is small (the ~5.5 ms aim compute is the floor) but it removes
the downstream np.asarray reparse and is the correct from_numpy interface.
NOTE: this is also why env_model now depends on the `numpy` rust crate; modules
that only do forward-sim (e.g. the graph bot) link it but never trigger a numpy
import since array ops are lazy.

Validation (all green after each change): env_model/validate_features.py checks,
against the official kaggle engine, that (a) the t+1/t+10/t_resolved frame caches
match kaggle stepping, (b) every valid action lands on its target at the predicted
turn, (c) masked-out-but-otherwise-legal actions are genuinely unreachable. Plus
`cargo test` replays every aim solution through the real engine for an exact check.

Further levers if needed: lower AIM_HORIZON (64) to drop very-slow long-range
single-ship shots; return numpy buffers instead of Python lists to cut marshalling.






